[It is advisable to keep a close eye on your animal's behavior. Monitoring temperatures and recording them twice daily is very handy at catching early signs of this rapidly moving disease. A slight increase in body temperature may be the only clinical sign early on.

Strict biosecurity in any facility is essential and it must become second nature to anyone working with horses.

Some of the biosecurity pointers in the piece from Kentucky should be heeded. Some are mentioned again here:

**Disinfect stalls before use,

**Never share water or feed buckets and tack or grooming equipment,

**Avoid unnecessary contact with other horses.

Additionally, people who work at multiple equine facilities should practice biosecurity measures by washing hands and changing footwear and clothing before entering each facility.

